\begin_layout Section
Financial Distress and Managerial Incentives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{L}=V_{U}+PV(TS)$
\end_inset

, the value of a leveraged firm increases with debt.
 Yet in reality firms do not tend to have too much debt.
 One reason is that too much debt might lead to bankruptcy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Financial Distress vs.
 Economic Distress
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
financial distress
\series default
 occures when a firm has difficulty meeting its debt obligations.
 A 
\series bold
default
\series default
 is when a firm fails to make the required interest or principal payments.
 Debt holders can claim rights on the assets of the firm and might even
 take legal ownership (through bankruptcy)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\series bold
economic distress
\series default
 is when a firm's continuation value is lower than its liquidation value,
 i.e its value as an ongoing business is lower that the market values of
 all its assets.
 Such company would be better off if it liquidates (considering the alternative).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A financial distress can exist without economic distress (you owe and don't
 pay back, but still have assets with market value).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Financial Distress and Bankruptcy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The possible responses of a firm to a financial distress are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Raise money
\series default
 - by issuing new debt or equity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Reorganize assets
\series default
 (sale assets / business units).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Work-out
\series default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - re-negotiate terms with debt holders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Reorganization
\series default
 (chapter 11) - through a plan which must be approved by creditors and sharehold
ers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Liquidation
\series default
 (chapter 7) - a trustee is appointed to liquidate the assets.
 Debt holders' interest payments are prioritized, but not the principal
