\begin_layout Subsection
Default and Bankruptcy in a Perfect Market
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Default, by itself, is not necessarily a problem.
 Consider a pharmaceutical company which focuses on innovation and is in
 process of developing a new drug.
 Being in the last stage of the FDA process, they anticipate the final decision
 by the end of the year.
 There are 2 possible scenarios: the firm will be worth $450M or $240M,
 according to whether the FDA approves the drug.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2 alternative capital structures are considered: all-equity financing, or
 use $300M debt which matures at the end of the year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first secnario, the value of the firm is $450M.
 If it doesn't have $300M in cash by the end of the year, it will be in
 a financial distress (can't meet its debt obligations), but won't be forced
 to default.
 It can raise money by a new loan / equity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the second scenario, the firm's value is $240M, equity holders get nothing
 and the creditors become the only shareholders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a perfect capital market, if the liquidation value is higher than the
 total assets value, there is economic distress in 
\series bold
any
\series default
 capital structure.
 Investors are 
\series bold
not
\series default
 worse off because of leverage.
 Thus, bankruptcy by itself doesn't reduce the value to investors (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

it is not the problem
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Efficient Liquidation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose the investors require 
\begin_inset Formula $6.5\%$
\end_inset

 on the debt.
 At the issuance day, they pay:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D=\frac{0.5(\$300+\$240)}{1+6.5\%}=\$253.52
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The return will be $300M (18.33%) in case of success and $240M (-5.33%) in
 case of failure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the FDA doesn't approve the drug, the firm will suffer from 
\series bold
economic distress
\series default
 (liquidation value higher than the continuation value).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is is efficient to liquidate a firm when the PV of future cash flows in
 case of continuation is below the cash flow from selling off all the assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At time of the bankruptcy, the bond holders benefit from the efficient liquidati
on.
 However, as both parites know it - different terms are expected (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

there are no free lunches
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Anticipating it, the investors will be willing to provide the funds at a
 lower payment in the good scenario.
 Thus, due to the efficient liquidation, 
\series bold
shareholders
\series default
 gain profit, as it allows the firm to issue debt at better terms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Bankruptcy Costs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In perfect markets, bankruptcy risk is not a disadvantage - it only shifts
 the ownership from the equity holders to the debt holders.
 It is not a realistic description of bankruptcy, as there are costs of
 bankruptcy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Direct costs - they reduce the value of the assets, which reduce the available
 money to the investors.
 They can be 3%-4%, but might be as high as 20%, depending on the firm's
 situation.
 They can be mitigated by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

working out
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - find a solution without going to the court, or by a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

prepackaged bankruptcy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - chapter 11 (reorganization).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Administrative costs: fees to legal experts, accountants, auctioneers, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Extra cost for creditors: they can anticipate the bankruptcy costs, thus
 give lower value to the shareholders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Opportunity cost of management time: instead of running the company, the
 management will focus on the debt, instead of positive CF projects, and
 perhaps even find another job.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Indirect costs
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Loss of customers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Loss of suppliers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Loss of employees
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Loss of receivables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Fire sale of assets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Inefficient liquidation (selling too early/late)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Forgone investment opportunities (a firm that faces bankrupcy won't look
 for new projects)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Costs to creditors
\end_layout

\end_deeper
