\begin_layout Subsection
Financial Distress Costs and Firm Value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Continuing the pharmaceutical firm example, if it fails to receive the FDA
 approval, it will be forced into bankruptcy.
 Assume the financial distress costs are estimated to $60 million.
 They lower the total value of the firm, and debtholders are those who bear
 them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But, as creditors can anticipate it, initially they pay less for the debt,
 thus the difference is in fact paid by the 
\series bold
shareholders
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Optimal Capital Structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
trade-off theory
\series default
 states that the firm chooses its capital structure by trading off the benefits
 of the tax shield vs.
 the costs of financial distress and agency costs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The present value of the expected bankruptcy costs is determined by the
 probability of a bankruptcy event and its magnitude.
 It helps to explain the debt level and use of leverage by firms.
 For example: airlines (low financial distress costs) vs.
 pharmaceutical firms (high costs).
\end_layout

